Issues:
[{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nA documented evaluation of 2–3 alternative hero animation libraries, producing a go/no-go recommendation before any rework of the existing canvas component begins.\n\nThis is a **HITL (human-in-the-loop)** spike. It produces a research document, not a code change. The portfolio owner must review and approve the recommendation before any hero rework begins.\n\n**Evaluation criteria:**\n- Bundle size impact\n- Angular compatibility (SSR-safe)\n- Visual impact relative to the existing `HeroCanvasComponent`\n- Ease of integration alongside the current canvas approach\n\n**Output:** a markdown document (e.g. `docs/spikes/hero-library-research.md`) covering:\n1. The candidates evaluated (developer-proposed + owner-referenced).\n2. A comparison table against the four criteria.\n3. A clear go/no-go recommendation: adopt a new library and rework the canvas, or keep `HeroCanvasComponent` and layer identity animations on top (as in #40).\n\n**This spike does not block #40.** The GSAP + typed.js identity layer (#40) is a safe, additive change that does not touch `HeroCanvasComponent`. A full canvas rework (if the spike recommends it) would be a separate issue opened after this spike closes.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Research document exists at `docs/spikes/hero-library-research.md`.\n- [ ] At least 2 libraries are evaluated against all four criteria.\n- [ ] Document includes a go/no-go recommendation with clear reasoning.\n- [ ] Portfolio owner has reviewed and approved (or rejected) the recommendation before any canvas rework begins.\n\n## Blocked by\n\nNone — can start immediately.","comments":[],"number":41,"title":"spike: hero library research + proposal"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nExtend the existing `HeroSectionComponent` to add an identity layer on top of the existing canvas: GSAP entrance animations for the name and CTA, and a typed.js typewriter effect for the title. Do not replace the component — extend it.\n\n**Existing file:** `src/app/pages/home/hero-section/hero-section.ts`\n**Extend, do not replace.**\n\n**Dependencies to install:**\n```\npnpm add gsap typed.js\n```\n\n**Behaviour:**\n- Install `gsap` and `typed.js` as production dependencies.\n- On `ngAfterViewInit`, guarded with `isPlatformBrowser` (SSR safety):\n  1. GSAP fades/slides the name element in.\n  2. After a 300 ms delay, typed.js starts the typewriter on the title element, cycling through: `\"Frontend Engineer\"`, `\"Angular Specialist\"`, `\"Team Lead\"`.\n  3. After typed.js `onComplete`, GSAP slides the CTA button up.\n- `prefers-reduced-motion`: skip GSAP and typed.js entirely — render name, title, and CTA immediately without animation.\n- `HeroCanvasComponent` is untouched — it remains the background layer. The identity layer sits above it at `z-10`.\n\n**Tests** (`hero-section.spec.ts`): extend existing spec —\n- Name and title are present in the DOM.\n- No SSR errors (platform guard works — mock `isPlatformBrowser` to return `false` in tests).\n- Animation libraries are nooped in the test environment (mock GSAP and typed.js).\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] `gsap` and `typed.js` are installed as production dependencies.\n- [ ] Name, title, and CTA render in the DOM on load.\n- [ ] Animations are guarded with `isPlatformBrowser` — no SSR errors.\n- [ ] `prefers-reduced-motion` skips all animations and renders content immediately.\n- [ ] `HeroCanvasComponent` template and logic are unchanged.\n- [ ] Updated spec passes with mocked animation libraries.\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\nNone — can start immediately.","comments":[],"number":40,"title":"feat: HeroSectionComponent — GSAP + typed.js identity layer"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nRestructure the existing `ResumeSectionComponent` from its current single-column layout to a two-column CSS Grid layout with a sticky sidebar on the left and a main content column on the right. Do not replace the component — extend it.\n\n**Existing file:** `src/app/pages/home/resume-section/resume-section.ts`\n**Extend, do not replace.**\n\n**Layout:**\n- Desktop (`md:` ≥ 768 px): `grid-cols-[280px_1fr]` CSS Grid. Left cell: `ProfileSidebarComponent`. Right cell: section heading, `TimelineComponent`, `EducationSectionComponent`, `SkillsSectionComponent` (top to bottom).\n- Mobile (< `md:`): single column. Sidebar renders as a compact horizontal strip above the main content.\n\n**Data wiring:**\n- `TimelineComponent`: pass `config.timeline`.\n- `EducationSectionComponent`: pass `config.education` and `config.certificates`.\n- `SkillsSectionComponent`: pass `config.skillCategories`.\n- `ProfileSidebarComponent`: reads config directly (no inputs needed).\n\n**Tests** (`resume-section.spec.ts`): extend existing spec — `ProfileSidebarComponent`, `TimelineComponent`, `EducationSectionComponent`, and `SkillsSectionComponent` all present in the DOM.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Two-column CSS Grid layout renders on `md:` and above.\n- [ ] Single-column layout renders below `md:`.\n- [ ] `ProfileSidebarComponent` renders in the left cell.\n- [ ] Right cell contains (top to bottom): section heading, `TimelineComponent`, `EducationSectionComponent`, `SkillsSectionComponent`.\n- [ ] All four components are present in the DOM per the updated spec.\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\n- #33 (ProfileSidebarComponent)\n- #35 (SkillsSectionComponent)\n- #37 (TimelineComponent — collapsed entry toggle)\n- #38 (EducationSectionComponent)","comments":[],"number":39,"title":"feat: ResumeSectionComponent — two-column layout restructure"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nA new Angular standalone component that renders the education entry and certification badges. Placed below `TimelineComponent` inside the main content column of the resume section.\n\nGenerate with: `pnpm ng generate component src/app/shared/components/education-section`\n\n**Inputs:**\n- `education: Education` (from `portfolio.config.ts`)\n- `certificates: Certificate[]` (from `portfolio.config.ts`)\n\n**Template:**\n- Education: rendered as a single timeline-style entry (institution, degree, date range).\n- Certificates: rendered as a horizontal row of compact badge cards, each showing title, issuer, and year.\n\n**Tests** (`education-section.spec.ts`):\n- Education entry renders with correct institution, degree, and date range.\n- Correct number of certificate cards render.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Component is standalone, signals-first, no RxJS.\n- [ ] `education` and `certificates` are declared as `input()` signals.\n- [ ] Education institution, degree, and date range are all visible in the template.\n- [ ] One badge card renders per certificate.\n- [ ] Each badge card shows title, issuer, and year.\n- [ ] `education-section.spec.ts` covers both cases.\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\n- #27","comments":[],"number":38,"title":"feat: EducationSectionComponent"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nExtend the existing `TimelineComponent` to hide entries where `collapsed === true` by default, and reveal them via a \"Show N earlier roles\" toggle button. Do not replace the component — extend it.\n\n**Existing file:** `src/app/shared/components/timeline/timeline.ts`\n**Extend, do not replace.**\n\n**Behaviour:**\n- Add `showEarlier = signal(false)` as internal state.\n- When `showEarlier` is `false`: filter out entries where `entry.collapsed === true` before rendering.\n- When `showEarlier` is `true`: render all entries.\n- The toggle button renders only when at least one entry has `collapsed: true`.\n- Toggle label: `\"Show ${collapsedCount} earlier roles ↓\"` when hidden; `\"Hide earlier roles ↑\"` when shown.\n\n**Tests** (`timeline.spec.ts`): extend existing spec —\n- All entries render when none have `collapsed: true`.\n- Entries with `collapsed: true` are hidden by default.\n- Toggle button is absent when no entries have `collapsed: true`.\n- Toggle button is present when at least one entry has `collapsed: true`; shows the correct count.\n- Clicking the toggle reveals the collapsed entries.\n- Clicking again hides them.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Entries with `collapsed: true` are hidden by default.\n- [ ] Toggle button renders only when at least one entry has `collapsed: true`.\n- [ ] Toggle label shows the correct count of collapsed entries.\n- [ ] Clicking toggle reveals collapsed entries; clicking again hides them.\n- [ ] Existing spec cases still pass; new toggle cases added.\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\n- #36 (TimelineEntryComponent — summary + visual connector)","comments":[],"number":37,"title":"feat: TimelineComponent — collapsed entry toggle"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nExtend the existing `TimelineEntryComponent` to render a one-sentence `summary` above the achievements list and add a visual vertical connector (dot + line) via CSS pseudo-elements. Do not replace the component — extend it.\n\n**Existing file:** `src/app/shared/components/timeline-entry/timeline-entry.ts`\n**Extend, do not replace.**\n\n**Template changes:**\n- If `entry.summary` is provided, render it as a muted `<p>` above the achievements `<ul>`.\n- If `entry.summary` is absent, render nothing in that position.\n- Add a vertical connector (dot at the top + line extending down) via CSS pseudo-elements on the host element. The connector visually links entries in the timeline.\n- Tech stack badges move below achievements (if they were above before).\n\n**No new inputs** — the component already has `entry: TimelineEntry`; the `summary` field is now part of that interface (added in #27).\n\n**Tests** (`timeline-entry.spec.ts`): extend existing spec —\n- `summary` renders as a paragraph when provided.\n- Nothing extra renders in the summary position when `summary` is absent.\n- Achievements count is still correct.\n- Tech chips still render.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] `entry.summary` renders as a muted paragraph above achievements when provided.\n- [ ] No summary element renders when `entry.summary` is absent.\n- [ ] Visual connector (dot + vertical line) is present via CSS on the host.\n- [ ] Existing spec cases still pass; new summary cases added.\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\n- #27","comments":[],"number":36,"title":"feat: TimelineEntryComponent — summary + visual connector"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nAn Angular standalone component that renders one `SkillsCategoryRowComponent` per skill category. Each row manages its own expand/collapse state independently.\n\nGenerate with: `pnpm ng generate component src/app/shared/components/skills-section`\n\n**Inputs:**\n- `categories: SkillCategory[]` (from `portfolio.config.ts`)\n\n**Template:** iterates `categories` with `@for` and renders a `SkillsCategoryRowComponent` per entry. No shared expand state across rows.\n\n**Tests** (`skills-section.spec.ts`): correct number of `SkillsCategoryRowComponent` instances render for the given input.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Component is standalone, signals-first, no RxJS.\n- [ ] `categories` is declared as an `input()` signal.\n- [ ] One `SkillsCategoryRowComponent` renders per category.\n- [ ] Each row's expand/collapse state is independent of the others.\n- [ ] `skills-section.spec.ts` verifies the correct row count.\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\n- #34 (SkillsCategoryRowComponent)","comments":[],"number":35,"title":"feat: SkillsSectionComponent"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nAn Angular standalone component that renders one skill category row. Tier 1 skills are always visible. Tier 2 skills are hidden by default, revealed by a per-row expand toggle.\n\nGenerate with: `pnpm ng generate component src/app/shared/components/skills-category-row`\n\n**Inputs:**\n- `category: SkillCategory` (from `portfolio.config.ts`)\n\n**Behaviour:**\n- Always renders the category name and all `tier1` chips.\n- When `tier2` is non-empty and `expanded` is `false`: renders a \"+ N more\" chip that acts as the expand trigger.\n- When `expanded` is `true`: renders all `tier2` chips and a \"Show less\" control.\n- When `tier2` is empty: no toggle renders at all.\n- `expanded = signal(false)` — internal state, not an input.\n- Expand/collapse uses a CSS `max-height` transition; no JS animation library.\n\n**Tests** (`skills-category-row.spec.ts`):\n- Tier 1 chips always present.\n- Tier 2 chips hidden by default.\n- Clicking the \"+ N more\" chip reveals Tier 2 chips and shows \"Show less\".\n- Clicking \"Show less\" collapses Tier 2.\n- No toggle renders when `tier2` is empty.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Component is standalone, signals-first, no RxJS.\n- [ ] `category` is declared as an `input()` signal.\n- [ ] `expanded` is an internal `signal(false)`.\n- [ ] All five acceptance test cases in the spec pass.\n- [ ] Expand/collapse uses CSS transition only — no JS animation library.\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\n- #27","comments":[],"number":34,"title":"feat: SkillsCategoryRowComponent"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nAn Angular standalone component that composes `AvatarComponent`, `ProfileBioComponent`, and `ProfileLinksComponent` into the sticky left sidebar of the resume section. Reads data from `portfolio.config.ts` directly — no inputs needed.\n\nGenerate with: `pnpm ng generate component src/app/shared/components/profile-sidebar`\n\n**Behaviour:**\n- On desktop (`md:` ≥ 768 px): renders as a vertical column, `position: sticky; top: 64px`, 280 px wide.\n- On mobile (< `md:`): collapses to a compact horizontal flex strip — avatar left, name + title + links right.\n- Passes `config.photo`, `config.hero.name`, `config.hero.title` to `AvatarComponent`.\n- Passes `config.bio` to `ProfileBioComponent`.\n- Passes `{ email: config.email, github: config.github, linkedin: config.linkedin }` to `ProfileLinksComponent`.\n\n**Tests** (`profile-sidebar.spec.ts`): all three sub-components render when config fields are populated; component mounts without errors.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Component is standalone, signals-first, no RxJS.\n- [ ] Renders `AvatarComponent`, `ProfileBioComponent`, and `ProfileLinksComponent`.\n- [ ] Sticky positioning (`top: 64px`) applied on `md:` breakpoint via Tailwind.\n- [ ] Mobile layout is a horizontal flex strip, not a vertical column.\n- [ ] `profile-sidebar.spec.ts` verifies all three sub-components are present in the DOM.\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\n- #30 (AvatarComponent)\n- #31 (ProfileBioComponent)\n- #32 (ProfileLinksComponent)","comments":[],"number":33,"title":"feat: ProfileSidebarComponent — orchestrator"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nA purely presentational Angular standalone component that renders contact links (email, GitHub, LinkedIn) using an icon + label pattern. Only non-null/undefined links render. Used as a sub-component inside `ProfileSidebarComponent`.\n\nGenerate with: `pnpm ng generate component src/app/shared/components/profile-links`\n\n**Inputs:**\n- `links: { email?: string; github?: string; linkedin?: string }`\n\n**Template:** a list of anchor elements, one per provided link. Each item shows an icon and the link text/label. Links that are absent from the input object do not render.\n\n**Tests** (`profile-links.spec.ts`):\n- All three links render when all three are provided.\n- Only the provided links render when some are omitted.\n- No links render when the object is empty.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Component is standalone, signals-first, no RxJS.\n- [ ] `links` is declared as an `input()` signal.\n- [ ] Each link renders only when its value is non-null/undefined.\n- [ ] Each rendered link is an `<a>` with the correct `href`.\n- [ ] `profile-links.spec.ts` covers all-three, subset, and empty cases.\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\n- #27","comments":[],"number":32,"title":"feat: ProfileLinksComponent"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nA purely presentational Angular standalone component that renders a bio string as a paragraph of text. Used as a sub-component inside `ProfileSidebarComponent`.\n\nGenerate with: `pnpm ng generate component src/app/shared/components/profile-bio`\n\n**Inputs:**\n- `bio: string`\n\n**Template:** a single `<p>` element with the bio text. No layout positioning — the parent sidebar handles that.\n\n**Tests** (`profile-bio.spec.ts`): bio text renders correctly.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Component is standalone, signals-first, no RxJS.\n- [ ] `bio` is declared as an `input()` signal.\n- [ ] The bio string is visible in the template.\n- [ ] `profile-bio.spec.ts` covers bio text rendering.\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\n- #27","comments":[],"number":31,"title":"feat: ProfileBioComponent"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nA purely presentational Angular standalone component that renders the engineer's photo, name, and title. Used as a sub-component inside `ProfileSidebarComponent`.\n\nGenerate with: `pnpm ng generate component src/app/shared/components/avatar`\n\n**Inputs:**\n- `photo: string` — image URL (optional, show a fallback icon when absent)\n- `name: string`\n- `title: string`\n\n**Template:** circular photo (or fallback icon), name in a heading, title in a muted subheading. No layout positioning — the parent sidebar handles that.\n\n**Tests** (`avatar.spec.ts`): photo renders with correct `src` and `alt`; fallback icon shown when `photo` is absent; `name` and `title` text render correctly.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Component is standalone, signals-first, no RxJS.\n- [ ] `photo`, `name`, `title` are declared as `input()` signals.\n- [ ] When `photo` is provided, an `<img>` renders with correct `src` and `alt` attributes.\n- [ ] When `photo` is absent, a fallback icon renders instead.\n- [ ] `name` and `title` are visible in the template.\n- [ ] `avatar.spec.ts` covers photo present, photo absent, name/title rendering.\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\n- #27","comments":[],"number":30,"title":"feat: AvatarComponent"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nPopulate `config.timeline` in `src/portfolio.config.ts` with all 8 career roles. Each entry must include `summary`, `achievements`, `techStack`, and `dateRange`. The two earliest roles (research positions, pre-2014) must have `collapsed: true`. This is a pure data-entry issue — no component changes.\n\n**Entries in display order (newest first):**\n\n```ts\n[\n  {\n    company: 'Backbase',\n    role: 'Senior Software Engineer',\n    dateRange: 'Aug 2025 – Present',\n    summary: 'Leading front-end engineers at Backbase LATAM, establishing standards and AI-assisted development workflows.',\n    achievements: [\n      'Leader of the front-end team, establishing standards, methodologies, and guidelines.',\n      'Collaborated with Backend teams, Core, Software Architects, and Business Analysts to discover, organize, and prioritize tasks.',\n      'Created and triaged over 200 tasks, focusing on small, well-defined units for fast developer pickup.',\n      'PR management, GitHub Actions, and repository handling using Angular 18 and AI-assisted development workflows.',\n    ],\n    techStack: ['Angular 18', 'TypeScript', 'GitHub Actions', 'AI-assisted development'],\n  },\n  {\n    company: 'Kunai / WEX',\n    role: 'Senior Software Engineer',\n    dateRange: 'Mar 2023 – Jun 2025',\n    summary: 'Co-led front-end development for WEX, owning component libraries and client branding.',\n    achievements: [\n      'Co-developed features and components with UI/UX and Backend teams.',\n      'Proposed and implemented generic, reusable components and utilities to reduce redundancy.',\n      'Maintained and refactored custom UI component libraries — achieved 40%+ reduction in bug introduction and 75% improvement in code reliability.',\n      'Built reusable Angular 14 components, integrated GraphQL APIs, managed application state for dynamic content rendering.',\n    ],\n    techStack: ['Angular 14', 'TypeScript', 'SCSS', 'GraphQL'],\n  },\n  {\n    company: 'The Ksquare Group / CBRE',\n    role: 'Senior Software Engineer',\n    dateRange: 'Mar 2021 – Dec 2022',\n    summary: 'Enhanced Angular components and drove performance improvements for a global public-facing application at CBRE.',\n    achievements: [\n      'Partnered with UX/UI teams to develop and refactor Angular components for a live production system.',\n      'Upgraded Angular versions to maintain long-term application performance and support.',\n      'Boosted application performance by 10% through bug fixes and flow optimizations.',\n      'Maintained 80%+ test coverage across new and existing repositories.',\n    ],\n    techStack: ['Angular', 'TypeScript', 'SCSS', 'Jest', 'Jasmine'],\n  },\n  {\n    company: 'EPAM Systems',\n    role: 'Senior Software Engineer',\n    dateRange: 'Sep 2019 – Mar 2021',\n    summary: 'Led UI modernisation and performance optimisation for data-intensive mobile applications, including an AngularJS→React migration.',\n    achievements: [\n      'Led UI modernisation and performance optimisation for a data-intensive mobile application.',\n      'Migrated a legacy AngularJS application to React, enhancing cross-platform support.',\n      'Developed a high-performance data-loading strategy, achieving under 3 seconds initial load time.',\n      'Implemented unit testing practices to ensure long-term stability.',\n    ],\n    techStack: ['React', 'AngularJS', 'HTML5', 'Responsive Web Design'],\n  },\n  {\n    company: 'Softtek / HP',\n    role: 'Full-Stack Developer',\n    dateRange: 'Jan 2019 – Aug 2019',\n    summary: 'Built enterprise Angular + Node.js application components for HP, translating business workflows into scalable UI.',\n    achievements: [\n      'Contributed to an enterprise-grade application using Angular and Node.js.',\n      'Collaborated with stakeholders to translate business workflows into scalable UI components.',\n      'Optimised backend integrations and database queries for enhanced responsiveness.',\n    ],\n    techStack: ['Angular', 'Node.js', 'HTML5', 'Responsive Web Design'],\n  },\n  {\n    company: 'IBM',\n    role: 'Full-Stack Developer',\n    dateRange: 'Feb 2016 – Oct 2018',\n    summary: 'Managed front-end development and release processes for a client-facing product under tight deadlines at IBM.',\n    achievements: [\n      'Managed front-end development and release processes for a client with tight deadlines.',\n      'Developed content and performed server maintenance using HTML5, CSS3, Angular 2, and PHP.',\n      'Collaborated with cross-functional teams to adapt to changing requirements.',\n    ],\n    techStack: ['Angular 2', 'HTML5', 'CSS3', 'PHP'],\n  },\n  {\n    company: 'Sistema Chiapaneco de Radio, Televisión y Cinematografía',\n    role: 'Software Developer & IT Support',\n    dateRange: 'Apr 2014 – Sep 2015',\n    summary: 'Developed process automation software and provided IT support for a state media organisation.',\n    achievements: [\n      'Developed software to automate processes within the organisation.',\n      'Provided IT support to various departments.',\n    ],\n    techStack: ['HTML', 'Responsive Web Design'],\n    collapsed: true,\n  },\n  {\n    company: 'Universidad Politécnica de Chiapas',\n    role: 'Software Developer & Researcher',\n    dateRange: 'Jan 2013 – Dec 2013',\n    summary: 'Research project to certify and validate physical documents using Java, encryption, and pattern recognition.',\n    achievements: [\n      'Research project to certify and validate documents, distinguishing originals from copies.',\n      'Applied Java, data encryption, signal processing, photography, and pattern recognition.',\n    ],\n    techStack: ['Java'],\n    collapsed: true,\n  },\n]\n```\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] `config.timeline` has exactly 8 entries in newest-first order.\n- [ ] Every entry has `company`, `role`, `dateRange`, `summary`, `achievements` (2–4 items), and `techStack`.\n- [ ] The two earliest entries (Sistema Chiapaneco, UPChiapas) have `collapsed: true`.\n- [ ] The six most recent entries have no `collapsed` field (or `collapsed: false`).\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\n- #27","comments":[],"number":29,"title":"data: populate timeline — 8 roles with summary, achievements, techStack, collapsed flag"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nFill in the stub fields added in #27 with real content: the bio string, five skill categories with tier assignments, one education entry, and three certification badge entries. This is a pure data-entry issue — no component changes.\n\n**Bio:**\n> \"Full-Stack Engineer with 10+ years building user-facing products across enterprise and start-up environments. Angular & TypeScript specialist who leads teams, owns features end-to-end, and cares deeply about the craft — from architecture to pixel.\"\n\n**Skill categories** (5, in this display order):\n\n| Category | Tier 1 | Tier 2 |\n|---|---|---|\n| Frontend | Angular, TypeScript, React, RxJS/NgRx, SCSS | JavaScript, HTML5, Tailwind, Next.js, Bootstrap, PrimeNG, Angular Material |\n| AI & Workflows | Cursor, LLMs, AI-assisted dev, GitHub Copilot | *(empty)* |\n| Backend & Data | Node.js, NestJS, PostgreSQL, Docker, Zod | GraphQL, MongoDB, Redis, MySQL, SQL Server, Java, Spring Boot, Express.js, Maven |\n| DevOps & Tooling | Git, GitHub Actions, Azure, AWS, Vercel | Jenkins, Webpack, Vite, Figma, Jira |\n| Testing & QA | Playwright, Jest, Vitest | Jasmine, Karma, Selenium, Test Automation |\n\n**Education:**\n- Institution: Universidad Politécnica de Chiapas\n- Degree: Software Engineer\n- Date range: 2010 – 2014\n\n**Certificates** (3):\n1. Build Deepsearch in TypeScript — issuer: *to confirm* — year: *to confirm*\n2. Agentic AI Engineering — issuer: *to confirm* — year: *to confirm*\n3. IBM Agile Advocate — issuer: IBM — year: *to confirm*\n\nNote: fill in issuer/year from the actual certificates; use placeholders only if genuinely unknown.\n\nAlso remove the now-unused flat `skills: string[]` array from the config if it survived the #27 restructure.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] `config.bio` matches the approved bio string exactly.\n- [ ] `config.skillCategories` has exactly 5 entries in the order: Frontend, AI & Workflows, Backend & Data, DevOps & Tooling, Testing & QA.\n- [ ] Each category's `tier1` and `tier2` arrays match the table above; no skill appears in both tiers or in two categories.\n- [ ] `config.education` is populated with UPChiapas degree data.\n- [ ] `config.certificates` has 3 entries with title, issuer, and year.\n- [ ] No flat `skills: string[]` field remains in the config.\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\n- #27","comments":[],"number":28,"title":"data: populate skills, bio, education, certs"},{"body":"## Parent\n\n#26\n\n## What to build\n\nRestructure `src/portfolio.config.ts` to be a flat typed constant with no `preview`/`full` namespace split (see ADR-0001). Add the new interfaces and fields required by the visual overhaul, populated with stubs so downstream component issues can depend on the correct type shape immediately.\n\n**Structural changes:**\n\n- Delete the `preview` and `full` namespaces from `PortfolioConfig`. All fields move to the top level.\n- Remove the dev-mode validator block at the bottom of the file (the `isDevMode()` guard that cross-checks `preview.timeline` vs `full.timeline` — it was designed for the gating model, which is dropped).\n- Extend `TimelineEntry` with two optional fields: `summary?: string` (one-sentence role context, shown above achievement bullets) and `collapsed?: boolean` (marks roles hidden by default — used for early research positions not central to the engineering narrative).\n- Add interface `SkillCategory { name: string; tier1: string[]; tier2: string[] }`.\n- Add interface `Education { institution: string; degree: string; dateRange: string }`.\n- Add interface `Certificate { title: string; issuer: string; year: number }`.\n- Add fields to `PortfolioConfig`: `bio: string`, `skillCategories: SkillCategory[]`, `education: Education`, `certificates: Certificate[]`.\n- Keep existing fields: `hero`, `photo`, `location`, `github`, `linkedin`, `timeline`.\n\n**Stub values** (real content comes in 1b and 1c):\n- `bio`: empty string `''`\n- `skillCategories`: empty array `[]`\n- `timeline`: keep the 2 existing entries as-is; do not populate the full 8 yet\n- `education`: stub object with empty strings\n- `certificates`: empty array `[]`\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] `PortfolioConfig` has no `preview` or `full` keys — all fields are top-level.\n- [ ] `TimelineEntry` interface includes `summary?: string` and `collapsed?: boolean`.\n- [ ] `SkillCategory`, `Education`, and `Certificate` interfaces are exported from `portfolio.config.ts`.\n- [ ] `PortfolioConfig` includes `bio: string`, `skillCategories: SkillCategory[]`, `education: Education`, `certificates: Certificate[]`.\n- [ ] The dev-mode validator block (`isDevMode()` guard) is removed.\n- [ ] The existing `ResumeSectionComponent` still compiles and renders without errors after the config shape change.\n- [ ] `pnpm run test:ci` passes.\n\n## Blocked by\n\nNone — can start immediately.","comments":[],"number":27,"title":"data: flatten PortfolioConfig — remove preview/full split, add new interfaces + field stubs"},{"body":"## Problem Statement\n\nThe current portfolio lacks visual structure and professional polish in the areas that matter most to visitors (recruiters, engineers, collaborators). The resume section is a flat, unstructured block — a basic profile header, a wall of ~50 undifferentiated skill chips, and a two-entry timeline with no descriptions or achievements. There is no bio, no sense of career narrative, and no visual hierarchy to guide the reader's eye. The hero section is visually impressive as a canvas animation but anonymous — it carries no identity signal and could belong to any developer.\n\nAs a result, visitors cannot quickly understand who Enrique is, what he specialises in, or what he has accomplished — the section fails its primary job.\n\n## Solution\n\nRedesign the resume section into a structured two-column layout (sidebar + main column) that mirrors the clarity of a polished CV. Enrich the content with a full 8-role work history, a bio, categorised collapsible skills, and an education/certifications section. Enhance the hero section with an identity layer (GSAP entrance animations + typed.js typewriter) on top of the existing canvas, and open a collaborative research spike for a potential full hero rework using a newer animation library.\n\n## User Stories\n\n### Resume — Layout & Structure\n1. As a recruiter visiting the portfolio, I want to see a two-column layout with a sidebar on the left and a timeline on the right, so that I can identify who Enrique is at a glance while reading his experience.\n2. As a visitor on desktop, I want the sidebar to remain sticky as I scroll through the timeline, so that Enrique's identity stays visible throughout my reading.\n3. As a visitor on mobile, I want the sidebar to collapse into a compact horizontal profile strip at the top of the resume section, so that the timeline gets full-width space without losing the identity context.\n4. As a visitor, I want a clear visual connector (vertical line + date nodes) on the timeline, so that I can track the chronological narrative of Enrique's career at a glance.\n\n### Resume — Sidebar\n5. As a recruiter, I want to see Enrique's photo, name, and title prominently in the sidebar, so that I immediately associate the portfolio with a real person.\n6. As a visitor, I want to read a short 2-3 sentence bio in the sidebar, so that I understand Enrique's focus and career aspiration in under 10 seconds.\n7. As a recruiter, I want to see contact links (email, GitHub, LinkedIn) in the sidebar, so that I can reach out without hunting through the page.\n8. As a developer of the portfolio, I want the avatar (photo + name + title), bio, and contact links to be separate components, so that each can be restyled or replaced independently without affecting the others.\n9. As a developer, I want the contact links component to support optional fields, so that links can be added or removed from config without breaking the layout.\n\n### Resume — Skills\n10. As a recruiter, I want skills grouped into labelled categories (Frontend, AI & Workflows, Backend & Data, DevOps & Tooling, Testing & QA), so that I can quickly scan the areas most relevant to an open role.\n11. As a visitor, I want the most important skills (Tier 1) to be visible immediately when I land on the skills section, so that I don't need to expand anything to see Angular, TypeScript, React, etc.\n12. As a visitor, I want each skill category row to be independently expandable, so that I can reveal the full depth of a specific category without expanding all of them.\n13. As a visitor, I want the AI & Workflows category to appear second (after Frontend), so that Enrique's investment in AI-assisted development is immediately visible as a differentiator.\n14. As a developer, I want skill tiers defined in config (not hardcoded in templates), so that updating which skills are Tier 1 vs Tier 2 requires no template changes.\n\n### Resume — Timeline\n15. As a recruiter, I want each timeline entry to show a one-sentence summary of the role, so that I can quickly understand the context before reading the achievement bullets.\n16. As a recruiter, I want to see 2-4 achievement bullets per role with metrics where available, so that I can assess impact rather than just responsibilities.\n17. As a visitor, I want to see compact tech stack badges on each timeline entry, so that I can scan the technologies used per role without reading the full text.\n18. As a visitor, I want the 6 most recent roles to be fully detailed by default, so that the timeline is rich without being overwhelming.\n19. As a visitor, I want the 2 earliest roles (pre-2016) to be collapsed behind a \"Show earlier roles\" toggle, so that I can access the full career history if I want it without it cluttering the default view.\n20. As a visitor, I want the collapsed earlier roles to expand inline (not a modal or new page), so that the reading flow is not interrupted.\n\n### Resume — Education & Certifications\n21. As a recruiter, I want to see Enrique's education (Universidad Politecnica de Chiapas, Software Engineer, 2010-2014) in a dedicated section below the timeline, so that the academic background is findable without dominating the page.\n22. As a recruiter, I want to see Enrique's certifications (Build Deepsearch in TypeScript, Agentic AI Engineering, IBM Agile Advocate) displayed as compact badge cards, so that his active investment in learning is visible at a glance.\n23. As a developer, I want education and certifications defined in portfolio.config.ts, so that adding a new certificate requires only a config change.\n\n### Hero — Identity Enhancement\n24. As a first-time visitor, I want to see Enrique's name and title animate in with a staggered entrance on page load, so that the hero feels intentional and polished rather than static.\n25. As a visitor, I want the title to cycle through Enrique's specialisations via a typewriter effect (e.g. \"Frontend Engineer\", \"Angular Specialist\", \"Team Lead\"), so that the hero communicates depth of identity in a compact space.\n26. As a visitor, I want the CTA button to animate in after the title, so that the entrance sequence draws my eye to the next action.\n27. As a developer, I want GSAP to handle entrance animations and typed.js to handle the typewriter effect, so that each concern has a dedicated, well-supported library with minimal overlap.\n28. As a visitor who prefers reduced motion, I want entrance animations to be skipped or minimised, so that the portfolio respects my accessibility preferences.\n\n### Hero — Research Spike\n29. As a developer, I want a documented evaluation of 2-3 alternative hero animation libraries (proposed by both developer and owner), so that a decision on a potential full hero rework is made with evidence rather than assumption.\n30. As the portfolio owner, I want to share reference works for hero evaluation, so that the final library choice reflects my aesthetic preferences alongside technical merit.\n31. As a developer, I want the research spike to produce a go/no-go recommendation before any rework of the existing canvas component begins, so that no current functionality is broken speculatively.\n\n### Content\n32. As the portfolio owner, I want all 8 roles in my work history populated in portfolio.config.ts with accurate dates, summaries, achievements, and tech stacks, so that the timeline reflects my full career narrative.\n33. As the portfolio owner, I want the sidebar bio to read: \"Full-Stack Engineer with 10+ years building user-facing products across enterprise and start-up environments. Angular & TypeScript specialist who leads teams, owns features end-to-end, and cares deeply about the craft -- from architecture to pixel.\"\n34. As the portfolio owner, I want the skill list rationalised and deduped across the 5 categories, so that no skill appears twice and the list reflects current relevance.\n\n## Implementation Decisions\n\n### Data layer -- portfolio.config.ts\n- Add interfaces: SkillCategory (name, tier1: string[], tier2: string[]), Education (institution, degree, dateRange), Certificate (title, issuer, year).\n- Add bio string field to preview.\n- Extend TimelineEntry with a summary?: string field (one-sentence role context, shown above bullets).\n- Populate all 8 timeline roles in full.timeline with summary, achievements, and techStack. The 6 recent roles map to preview.timeline; the 2 earliest (IBM, Sistema Chiapaneco) are present in full.timeline only and rendered behind the \"Show earlier roles\" toggle.\n- Replace the flat skills: string[] array with skillCategories: SkillCategory[] -- 5 entries in the order: Frontend, AI & Workflows, Backend & Data, DevOps & Tooling, Testing & QA.\n- Add education: Education and certificates: Certificate[] to preview.\n\n### Shared components -- sidebar\n- AvatarComponent -- inputs: photo, name, title. Presentational only.\n- ProfileBioComponent -- input: bio: string. Presentational only.\n- ProfileLinksComponent -- input: links: { email?: string; github?: string; linkedin?: string }. Renders only non-null links. Uses icon + text pattern.\n- ProfileSidebarComponent -- orchestrates the three above. Handles position: sticky; top: <header-height> on md: breakpoint. Collapses to horizontal strip below md:.\n\n### Shared components -- skills\n- SkillsCategoryRowComponent -- inputs: category: SkillCategory. Internal expanded = signal(false). Always renders tier1 chips; conditionally renders tier2 chips + \"Show less\" when expanded; renders \"+ N more\" count chip when collapsed. Animation: max-height CSS transition, no JS animation library needed.\n- SkillsSectionComponent -- input: categories: SkillCategory[]. Renders one SkillsCategoryRowComponent per category. No shared expand/collapse state -- each row is independent.\n\n### Shared components -- timeline\n- TimelineEntryComponent -- extend template to render entry.summary as a muted paragraph above the achievements list. Tech stack badges move below achievements. Visual connector (dot + vertical line) added via CSS pseudo-elements on the host, not a separate element.\n- TimelineComponent -- add showEarlier = signal(false) internal state. Entries beyond index 5 are hidden behind a \"Show 2 earlier roles\" button. Button toggles showEarlier. The toggle button is only rendered when entries().length > 6.\n\n### New component -- education\n- EducationSectionComponent -- inputs: education: Education, certificates: Certificate[]. Renders education as a single timeline-style entry, certs as a row of small cards (title + issuer + year). Placed below TimelineComponent inside the main column.\n\n### Resume section restructure\n- ResumeSectionComponent -- replace current single-column template with a two-column CSS Grid layout (grid-cols-[300px_1fr] on md:, single column below). Left cell: ProfileSidebarComponent. Right cell (top to bottom): section heading, TimelineComponent, EducationSectionComponent, SkillsSectionComponent.\n\n### Hero enhancement\n- HeroSectionComponent -- install gsap and typed.js as dependencies. On ngAfterViewInit (browser-only, guarded with isPlatformBrowser): run a GSAP timeline that fades/slides in name (0ms), title typed.js instance starts (300ms delay), CTA button slides up (typed.js onComplete callback). Respect prefers-reduced-motion -- if set, skip GSAP and typed.js, render text immediately.\n- The existing HeroCanvasComponent is untouched by this story.\n\n### Hero research spike (separate story)\n- Produce a written evaluation (GitHub comment or discussion) covering 2-3 candidate libraries. Criteria: bundle size, Angular compatibility, visual impact, SSR safety. Decision requires owner sign-off before implementation begins.\n\n### Two-column layout responsive breakpoint\n- Desktop (md: = 768px+): grid-cols-[280px_1fr], sidebar sticky at top: 64px (header height).\n- Mobile (below md:): single column, sidebar renders as a horizontal flex strip (avatar left, name/title/links right), no sticky behaviour.\n\n## Testing Decisions\n\nA good test for this codebase describes observable behaviour from the outside -- what the template renders given a set of inputs or user interactions -- not internal signal values or private methods. Follow the pattern established in timeline.spec.ts and timeline-entry.spec.ts: create the component with TestBed, provide required inputs, query the DOM, and assert on rendered output or emitted events.\n\n### Modules with logic (high priority)\n- SkillsCategoryRowComponent -- test: Tier 1 chips render by default; Tier 2 chips are hidden; clicking \"show more\" reveals Tier 2 chips and changes button label; clicking \"show less\" collapses them again. Edge case: category with empty Tier 2 shows no toggle button.\n- TimelineComponent -- test: with 6 or fewer entries, no \"show earlier\" button renders; with more than 6 entries, entries beyond index 5 are hidden and the toggle button is present; clicking the button reveals all entries.\n- TimelineEntryComponent -- test: summary renders when provided; summary is absent from DOM when not provided; achievement list renders correct count; tech stack chips render; logo renders when provided, falls back gracefully when absent.\n- ProfileLinksComponent -- test: email link renders when provided, is absent when omitted; same for github and linkedin; all three render together when all provided.\n\n### Modules presentational (low priority)\n- AvatarComponent -- test: photo renders with correct src/alt when provided; fallback icon shows when photo is absent.\n- ProfileBioComponent -- test: bio text renders.\n- ProfileSidebarComponent -- test: renders all three sub-components when all inputs are provided.\n- SkillsSectionComponent -- test: renders one row per category.\n- EducationSectionComponent -- test: education entry renders; correct count of cert cards renders.\n\n### Hero\n- HeroSectionComponent -- test: name and title render in the DOM (animation libraries are mocked/noop in test environment); no errors thrown on SSR (platform check guards).\n\n## Out of Scope\n\n- Hero full rework (covered by the research spike story -- implementation deferred until library decision is made).\n- Contact form or any backend/API work.\n- Projects showcase section.\n- Token-gated full resume (/resume?token=).\n- SEO meta tags or Open Graph.\n- Dark/light mode theming changes beyond what the existing ThemeService already handles.\n- Vercel deployment or CI pipeline changes.\n- Any changes to HeaderComponent or FooterComponent.\n\n## Further Notes\n\n- The existing HeroCanvasComponent is not modified in this story -- it continues to run as the background layer. The identity layer sits above it at z-10 (already in the current template).\n- Company logos for timeline entries (the existing logo? field on TimelineEntry) are optional and out of scope for this story -- the config shape supports them, but sourcing and optimising the assets is a separate task.\n- The portfolio.config.ts dev-mode validation guard (checking preview.timeline vs full.timeline key alignment) will need to be updated once the preview/full split is revised to accommodate the 6/2 entry split.\n- The ready-for-agent label is applied -- this issue is fully groomed and can be picked up for implementation without further clarification.\n","comments":[],"number":26,"title":"feat: portfolio visual overhaul — resume section redesign + hero enhancement"}]

# ISSUES

GitHub issues are provided at start of context. Parse it to get open issues with their bodies and comments.

You will work on the AFK issues only, not the HITL ones.

You've also been passed a file containing the last few commits. Review these to understand what work has been done.

If all AFK tasks are complete, output <promise>NO MORE TASKS</promise>.

# TASK SELECTION

Pick the next task. Prioritize tasks in this order:

1. Critical bugfixes
2. Development infrastructure

Getting development infrastructure like tests and types and dev scripts ready is an important precursor to building features.

3. Tracer bullets for new features

Tracer bullets are small slices of functionality that go through all layers of the system, allowing you to test and validate your approach early. This helps in identifying potential issues and ensures that the overall architecture is sound before investing significant time in development.

TL;DR - build a tiny, end-to-end slice of the feature first, then expand it out.

4. Polish and quick wins
5. Refactors

# EXPLORATION

Explore the repo.

# IMPLEMENTATION

Complete the task.

# FEEDBACK LOOPS

Before committing, run the feedback loops:

- `pnpm run test` to run the tests
- `pnpm run typecheck` to run the type checker

# COMMIT

Make a git commit. The commit message must:

1. Include key decisions made
2. Include files changed
3. Blockers or notes for next iteration

# THE ISSUE

If the task is complete, close the original GitHub issue.

If the task is not complete, leave a comment on the GitHub issue with what was done.

# FINAL RULES

ONLY WORK ON A SINGLE TASK.
